AVM1: Optimize name normalization

Name normalization is somewhat heavyweight right now, because it needs to check the SWF version to decide whether to lower-case names. It also doesn't fast-path numbers. This patch fixes both of these issues by moving the operation into a SWF version-dependent implementation on `AVM1Context`, avoiding runtime checks, and optimizing the implementations a bit.

Remove some non-required lower-casing of property names

These are in places where we're guaranteed to already have lower-cased the names. To ensure it stays that way, I made the preexisting asserts stronger.

Don't escape AVM1 property names starting with "_"

This was introduced to prevent triggering JS engines' special behavior, such as setting the proto when the property name is `"__proto__"`. That's not required, however: all the special behavior that's there doesn't apply in this case: `__proto__` only has special behavior if used as a literal, not when it's the value of a variable. `__noSuchMethod__`, which only exists in SpiderMonkey, does have special behavior even when contained in a variable. However, that special behavior is only triggered if a missing method is called on the containing object, which we never do on the AVM1 property holders.

Improve behavior of PerspectiveProjection to match Flash much more closely

The behavior of `PerspectiveProjection` is interesting in that it can either be completely independent of any `DisplayObject`, or be a live view into one. Creating an instance using `new PerspectiveProjection()` causes the former, getting one via `displayObject.transform.perspectiveProjection` the latter, even though that returns a copy instead of the same instance every time.

This makes the implementation a bit annoying because we need to either store/retrieve the `projectionCenter` and `fieldOfView` values on the instance itself, or on the displayObject it's a view for.

Bug 1148805 - Cache MovieClip child names in AVM1MovieClip for faster lookup

Cache MovieClip child names in AVM1MovieClip for faster lookup

This requires keeping a name-keyed map of `AVM1MovieClip` children and keeping it up to date whenever anything of the following happens:
- A child is added
- A child is removed
- A child's depth changes

The latter is required because if there are multiple children with the same name, the lowest one is used when looking up that name.

Ensure buffer availability for more BitmapData operations

For some `BitmapData` operations we already called `_ensureBitmapData` to request the underlying buffer from the GFX backend if it's not already available. This patch extends that to more operations.

Perform system.Security.allowDomain for cross-domain SWFs only, instead of image files, too

Currently we delay loading any files with `Loader#load` one event turn and only actually perform the load if the parent SWF has called `system.Security.allowDomain` with a string that allows the loadee's domain. This is to mitigate against a loaded SWF file breaking our sandboxing and reaching into the parent SWF. (Which it is allowed to once `allowDomain` has been called.) The problem is that that prevents loading of image files, too, even though those can't ever perform the attacks we want to prevent.

With this patch, we instead perform the check after the file has started loading, and only if it's a SWF file. In case the check fails, we stop loading and dispatch an asynchronous error event on the `Loader`'s `contentLoaderInfo`.

Catch errors in event handlers per target and properly continue execution. r=tobytailor

`EventDispatcher#dispatchEvent` aborts all event dispatching *for a specific target* upon unhandled exceptions in a handler. It logs a warning and then continues orderly execution. That includes dispatching the same event on other targets in the same, and in other phases. I.e., if a capturing phase handler throws, other capture phase handlers are run and the target and bubbling phases continue as expected. The included tracetest covers all these cases by throwing in all handlers.

Merge pull request #2174 from tschneidereit/interpreter-frame

Factor most state from _interpret into InterpreterFrame instance

Factor most state from _interpret into InterpreterFrame instance

 Four reasons for doing this:
 - It's easier to follow.
 - It makes debugging easier because it makes it trivial to skip over the setup of all this state instead of having to single-step through it.
 - It's very slightly faster (~5% by my rough measurements).
 - It paves the way for extracting rarely used bytecodes into a new function to make the main interpreter loop much lighter-weight and better optimizable.

 But really, the first two are the motivation.

Merge pull request #2164 from mozilla/arguments-callee

Add support for arguments.callee

Implement support for arguments.callee

This is quite annoying to support, because it does very different things for free functions compared to traits. Traits are extracted into `MethodClosure`s, including memoization and all that.

Not supported is `arguments.callee` in constructors. It's entirely unclear to me what anybody would use it for: it returns a `MethodClosure` bound to the current instance that can be called and that then executes the constructor's code again on that instance. It can't be `new`'d though. I somewhat doubt that there's code out there that relies on this working, but who knows.

Rewrite of most of the AVM2 component, the core of the AVM1

Rewrite of most of the AVM2 component, the core of the AVM1, plus lots of other changes to adapt to said rewrites

This is a __huge__ commit, because it's a squashed version of 777 individual commits. Taken together, they replace the vast majority of code in src/avm2 and much in src/avm1. Gone are the AVM2 JIT, the old interpreter, and huge amounts of code.

The new VMs (both AVM1 and AVM2) contain completely new implementations of the languages meta-object protocols and name resolution schemes that're much closer to what Flash is doing on a fundamental level, enabling better in-depth compatibility throughout.

Also, for AVM2 we have vastly improved test coverage, largely through importing the Tamarin test suite and a harness that runs that entire test suite in a ridiculous 25 seconds. Current pass rate: ~96.5%. (Compared to ~80% to 85% before all this.)

The original commits can, for the time being, be found in the [redux branch](https://github.com/mozilla/shumway/tree/redux).

    Implement out-of-line exception handling in the interpreter
        The interpreter's main loop should be as small as possible, so cluttering it up with type checks and exception handling isn't ideal. OTOH, lots of operations can throw JS exceptions, which we have to turn into AS3 ones before letting content script loose on them. This is achieved by calling a conversion function in the interpreter's `catch` block that takes the current Bytecode and values of various variables and returns a valid exception if it can. Otherwise it at least wraps the exception into a valid one so the internal one doesn't leak.

Merge pull request #2030 from tschneidereit/master

Slim down method trait trampolines and memoizers

Cache resolved trait function and memoizer in MethodInfo

The same traits are installed in all inheriting classes over and over again. Right now, we also resolve the same functions over and over again, for no good reason whatsoever. With this patch, we instead store them on the trait's `MethodInfo` once and then reuse that cached version, both for the function itself and the memoizer. For lazy compilation-trampolines, each new installation of the trait prototype gets added to the list of getters to patch.

Merge pull request #1856 from tschneidereit/parser

Bug 1035170 - Rewrite SWF parsing to a scan-first, parse tags on demand approach

Bug 1035170 - Implement lazy SWF parsing

This is a monster-patch as it's the result of squashing together 81 individual patches. It contains a full refactoring of how SWF files are parsed and the results managed.

In the new system, SWFs aren't deeply parsed and all symbols and other tags extracted. Instead, they're scanned through, detecting all symbols, frames, and code blocks. The player is notified of these tags, but they're only deeply parsed upon first usage. Even then, the `SWFFile` class that represents the loaded SWF doesn't hold on to the parsed tag. It is up to the playback system to decide whether that's required or not. For now, it does happen in most cases, but we might decide to hold most parsing results temporarily only.

In the following, I tried to include the important commit messages for the original patches squashed down into this one. The original patches themselves are available in [a branch](https://github.com/tschneidereit/shumway/tree/parser-unsquashed) in @tschneidereit's fork.

Bug fix in SoundStreamHead: StreamSoundSampleCount field is a UI16, not UI32

Disable usage of DOM Workers in fakeSyncWorker.ts for now
This creates lots and lots of IO events, overwhelming browsers in some cases. Also, it most certainly imposes substantial overhead.

Move initialization of loaded frames from Loader into MovieClip

Null out the SWFFile's decompressor after loading is completed, to free its memory.

Don't treat BMPs as eagerly-decoded images

Increases height of profiler output panel to accomodate parser timeline

Remove some somewhatImplemented warnings
These got in the way of trace tests after some changes to how logging of warnings works.

Add timeouts to the GNU parallel command. (Original patch by @mbebenita)

Add simple DOM stubs for Image, URL and Blob to the shell testing harness. (Original patch by @mbebenita)

Adds profiling option -o to the shell driver. This let's you dumps out timeline events to stdout when verbose mode is also on. (Original patch by @mbebenita)

Optimize DataBuffer access by providing methods for writing multiple values at the same time. Also, lazify the way views are allocated since not all views are always needed. (Original patch by @mbebenita)

Switches AVM1Utils.addEventListenerProxy to a native implementation

Optimize parsing of AVM1 ClipEvents
And moved their application to avm1lib. Before, it was partly in FrameDelta#_initialize, partly in the late Sprite#_initAVM1Bindings.
This also fixes the mapping of some of the ClipEvents to equivalent AVM2 events. Some aren't trivially mapped, so more work has to be done there. Those will show a warning at least when they're used.

Add new test for mouse events on nested AVM1 objects and reactivate some existing tests
The existing tests where disabled before the nat branch merge and then forgotten about.

Give PromiseWrapper a `then` method

Delay committing Loader updates until the right point in the event loop

Support initialization from Uint8Array in source instead of special-casing BinarySymbol in ByteArray initializer

Change how resolved symbols get stored on ASClasses
Instead of having the Symbol ctor do that, the symbolResolver now does it. Not only is that cleaner, it's also required to make embedded images work: for those, the symbol is associated with a subclass of `Bitmap`, but we create a `BitmapSymbol` for the actual data. This was then stored on `flash.display.BitmapData`. Not ideal.

Delay updating contentLoaderInfo.bytesLoaded until all frame assets embedded up until that offset have been resolved

Merge pull request #1820 from tschneidereit/master

Delay all immediately-executed ABC blocks until all frame assets have been resolved

Delay all immediately-executed ABC blocks until all frame assets have been resolved

An ABC block can and, in many cases, will rely on other assets being available. It might rely on the fact that an embedded image comes before it in the SWF file, so it can safely just access the image. In delaying the ABC block's execution until all previous assets have become available, we guarantee that that actually works.

(Note: that's not the end of the story, sadly. Code also can rely on just the `bytesLoaded` value matching some expectations, so we have to delay reporting bytes as loaded until their contents are fully available, too. But that's for another bug.)

Improve as3 Loader reftest to also test which frame events are dispatched in

The previous two patches fix parts of our Loader event dispatching behavior in ways that weren't tested by this reftest before.

Dispatch PROGRESS events every event loop turn if actual loading progress was made

 ... instead of only once when loading starts and then again when loading is complete. This regressed in Spring, without anyone noticing. Which isn't all that surprising: it's close to impossible to build a good, deterministic testcase for this.

Dispatch loader events after all frame events in the event loop

Because Flash does that, too. To pull this off, we have to also delay committing frames from the parser until the right point of the event loop. For everything but the main SWF's first frame, that is: committing that is what triggers any code execution whatsoever. ... Which we might want to change at some point, too.

Avoid calling isNumericString() from isNumeric().

Avoid calling isNumericString() from isNumeric().

Most calls to isNumeric() are for identifiers, and isNumericString()
ends up being called, which is expensive because it creates a new
string.

This patch adds a simple check that avoids the need to call isIndex()
and isNumericString() in these cases. This avoids 10s of MiBs of
allocations per lap in the racing demo.

Merge pull request #1585 from nnethercote/slimmer-asserts

Avoid excess allocations in assert().

Avoid excess allocations in assert().

The use of `...args` caused TypeScript to emit some silly code that did
some unnecessary copying of the `arguments` array, and the use of
`arguments` caused additional allocations.

This change removes `...args`; only one message argument is now allowed,
and you have to pre-concatenate. This only affected ~20 assertions.

This reduces the cumulative allocations done by the JS engine while
starting up the racing demo by 34%, from 192 MB to 127 MB. These
allocations wouldn't happen in release mode, but there are so many of
them that it's worth fixing them even for non-release mode.

Merge pull request #1411 from tschneidereit/nat

Memory optimizations/ leak fixes

Change the SWF parser's readBinary function to copy bytes instead of returning subarrays

At least for all usages that don't further process the bytes but just pass them on to the script thread. Otherwise, they just keep the entire SWF parsing buffer alive, potentially multiple times. Reduces memory usage by up to 40% (i.e., a certain specific case I measured goes from 263MB to 152MB.)

Lazify FrameDelta initialization

Most frames will only be shown way after they've been initially created, so we can just delay the calculations required for initializing them until that time. That also reduces memory usage quite substantially for SWFs with long timelines.
Make sure to begin paths when building clip rects.

Merge pull request #1366 from tschneidereit/nat

Shape fixes

Store shape fill gradients' focalPoint as fixed8 instead of byte

Turns out these can have fractional parts.

Don't auto-close strokes

For fills, we have to manually draw a line connecting the first and the last coordinates of the path. For shapes, not so much.

Emit endFill/endLine commands at the end of a shape path

Otherwise, we'll happily continue playing back path commands for the last fill in the renderer while line paths are played back, and only apply the fill once all paths are complete.

Store lineStyle's thickness as twips in coordinates

Turns out the thickness isn't rounded to the nearest pixel after all, but stored - and interpreted - in twips. Because the commands buffer is in bytes, the thickness is written into the coordinates instead. In some ways this is even less dirty than the previous solution. It wastes two bytes, but line styles aren't set that frequently, so this is fine.

Merge pull request #1161 from tschneidereit/master

AVM1 loadVariables and getURL

Incomplete support for AVM1 loadMovie

The AVM1 parts *should* be done, but there are issues in Loader preventing this from working:
- Loader assumes that all loaded content is part of the display list when trying to construct the first frame
- the Loader instance doesn't have an AS2Context, and no way of getting one, because it doesn't have access to the stage without being part of the display list

This needs a workaround for native JS objects like Number, Boolean, etc.. because they don't fit into our trait/dynamic prototype scheme.

runtime: Fix bug when extending (wrapping around) native classes such as Namespace.

Native classes that are reflected to AS3 need to have two prototypes, so:

function C(); C.prototype = Object.create(d);

when used in conjunction with |extendNative| the C.prototype becomes the traitsPrototype and C.prototype.__proto__ becomes the dynamic prototype.

runtime: Add a native length property on AS3 Object and override it in subclasses.

This fixes code such as "Array.prototype.push.call({length: 3}, 2)" where the length property needs to be reflected to the underlying object length so that the JS native push function works.

native: Support istype on constructprop Strings/Numbers

constructprop will always compile into a `new TYPE()`. In any sane type
system, `new String("foo") === "foo"` is an assertion that holds.
Unfortunately, this is JavaScript, so `new String("foo")` is something
that doesn't do what you want out of the box. In order to support this,
we need to make sure we call valueOf() on the types to convert them into
their literal values before checking their intrinsic types.

Traits/prototype rework to prevent leaking traits

The prototype chain for classes now look like the following.

Suppose for classes C, D, that D <: C. Let arrow denote the "is prototype of"
relation.

Class.public$prototype returns instance.dynamicPrototype ===
Object.getPrototypeOf(instance.prototype), with the chaining done as follows:

C.dynamicPrototype <- C.prototype [traits]
        ^
        |
        |
D.dynamicPrototype <- D.prototype [traits]

That is, D.prototype's [[Prototype]] is D.dynamicPrototype, which is what gets
returned for Class.public$prototype.

D.prototype contains the traits and isn't visible to AVM-land.

This also lets all the traits be resolved before dynamic properties.

compiler: Use variable pool instead of overwriting a temporary

In certain circumstances we do dumb things like using the first temporary
or overwriting the entire temporary. For code where something like:

    getProperty(s0, $C[1]);

is on the stack, when setting it to a slot, this becomes:

    s0 = obj.types[1];
    obj[obj.slots[1]] = getProperty(s0, $C[1]);

which is obviously clobbered and wrong. So, we need to have some way
to track that temporaries aren't getting clobbered; that is, track which
ones we do and do not use. Thankfully, we already have such a tracker:
the VariablePool. Use this to record temporaries.

Still use the temporary stack when flushing the temporaries out.

This makes crypto-aes.js work when using the compiler.

compiler: Do a fast path for loop indexes

Code like:

  var a = [1, 2, 3], n = a.length, i;
  for (i = 0; i < n; i++)
    print(a[i]);

Will get compiled to something like:

    getlocal 1 /* a */
    getpropstrict ::length
    setlocal 2 /* n */

    /* i = 0; */
    pushbyte 0
    setlocal 3 /* i */

  L1:
    /* i < n; */
    getlocal 3
    getlocal 2
    ifgt L2

    /* print(a[i]); */
    findpropstrict ::print
    getlocal 1
    getlocal 3
    getproperty []:: /* MultinameL with a public namespace */
    callproperty ::print 1

    /* i++ */
    inclocal_i 3
    jump L1;

  L2:
    returnvoid

In a tight loop, it's a bad idea to require a runtime lookup to
resolve the MultinameL. So, special case the runtime getProperty
code in the compiler to fast case this common path.

Rewrite restructuring algorithm to be understandable by people other than me

- Now uses a relooper-style algorithm, which is clearly O(|E|) for the CFG.
- No longer hoist anything into loops. Modern CPUs' icache might start
  speculative cache anything inside conditionals inside a loop, and if we
  hoist too much inside it could be bad for perf even though we're saving one
  conditional and assignment. Alon didn't see any improvement when hoisting.
- Relatedly, no long breaks/continues for now.

Fix recomputing dominance info; misc bug fixes

- Block IDs are no longer in reverse postorder due to node splitting. The
  dominance algorithm instead expects an array of blocks in reverse postorder.

- The first attempt to incrementally recompute dominance info was horribly
  wrong. The current algorithm after splitting a SCC still needs to re-walk
  the entire graph to get a new reverse postordering of blocks, but it can use
  the old dominator information for all nodes whose predecessors did not
  change, i.e. nodes outside of the SCC set, cloned nodes, and nodes that
  have cloned nodes as successors.
